{"title_page": "The Order of Things (album)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Order of Things\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]]\n| cover      = The Order of Things.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 24, 2015\n| recorded   = 2014\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Alternative metal]]|[[melodic metalcore]]}}\n| length     = 48:48<br />52:20 (Japanese version)\n| label      = [[Razor & Tie]]\n| producer   = Josh Wilbur\n| prev_title = [[A War You Cannot Win]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[Madness (All That Remains album)|Madness]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Order of Things\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = No Knock\n | single1date = November 24, 2014\n | single2     = [[This Probably Won't End Well]]\n | single2date = January 13, 2015\n | single3     = [[Tru-Kvlt-Metal]]\n | single3date = February 10, 2015\n | single4     = For You\n | single4date = May 13, 2015\n | single5     = Victory Lap\n | single5date = December 8, 2015<ref>{{cite web|last1=Al-Sharif|first1=Rabab|title=All That Remains give fans a look at life on the road in video for new single \"Victory  Lap\"|url=http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/all_that_remains_premiere_video_for_new_single_victory_lap|publisher=Alternative Press|accessdate=January 22, 2016|date=December 8, 2015}}</ref>\n | single6     = Criticism and Self-Realization\n | single6date = May 4, 2016\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings \n| rev1 = [[About.com]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"About review\">{{cite web | url = http://heavymetal.about.com/od/allthatremains/fl/All-That-Remains-The-Order-Of-Things-Review.htm | title = All That Remains - The Order Of Things Review |publisher=[[MetalSucks]]|  first = Todd | last = Lyons | accessdate = February 21, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[Artistdirect]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Artistdirect review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/album-review-all-that-remains-the-order-of-things-5-out-of-5-stars/11314127 | title = Album Review: All That Remains \"The Order of Things\" \u2013 5 out of 5 stars |publisher=[[Artistdirect]]|  first = Rick | last = Florino| date = February 11, 2015 | accessdate = February 21, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-order-of-things-mw0002802858 | title = Album Review: All That Remains \"The Order of Things\" \u2013 2.5 out of 5 stars |publisher=[[AllMusic]] | first = Christopher | last = Monger}}</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Blabbermouth.net]]\n| rev4Score = 7.5/10<ref name=\"Blabbermouth review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/cdreviews/the-order-of-things/ | title = All That Remains - \"The Order of Things\" |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|  first = Ray | last = Van Horn, Jr.}}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[MetalSucks]]\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|1.5|5}}<ref name=\"MetalSucks review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.metalsucks.net/2015/02/17/remains-discuss-whiny-lead-singer-whose-controversies-far-outshadow-bands-bland-music/ | title = All That Remains To Discuss Is A Whiny Lead Singer Whose Controversies Far Outshadow His Band\u2019s Bland Music |publisher=[[MetalSucks]]| first = Kip | last = Wingerschmidt | date = February 17, 2015 | accessdate = February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev6 = [[Ultimate-guitar]]\n| rev6score = {{Rating|5.5|10|score=5.3 stars on a 10 point scale}}<ref name=Guitar>http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/reviews/compact_discs/all_that_remains/the_order_of_things/index.html</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Order of Things''''' is the seventh studio album by [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]]. It was released on February 24, 2015, on [[Razor & Tie]] Records. ''The Order of Things'' is the first studio album to be produced by Josh Wilbur. It is also the final album to feature bassist [[Jeanne Sagan]] due to her departure from the band in September 2015. The album debuted at number 25 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 19,150 copies in its first week only in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metalinsider.net/columns/metal-by-numbers/metal-by-numbers-34-the-kid-is-alright|title=Metal By Numbers 3/4: The Kid is alright|date=March 4, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe album was recorded and produced by Josh Wilbur.\n\nThe first song released from the album was \"No Knock\". The song was first posted by Labonte's pseudo-account called \"Harrison Ford\" with the video that was released on November 14, 2014 entitled \"You Found Me\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wxqQhxK35WY</ref>\nIt later on was posted by [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]] official [[YouTube]] Channel.\n\n[[Philip Labonte|Phil Labonte]] and producer Josh Wilbur wrote the lyrics for the album together, which is the first time in All That Remains catalogue. Phil Labonte stated about working with Josh: \"Honestly, the test for me is, like, when me and Josh [got] done, 'cause we wrote the melodies and the lyrics together; none of the vocals were done before I actually sat down with [[Josh wilbur|Josh]]. This is the first time that anyone has ever had any kind of input onto lyrics. But Josh is the only guy that's actually worked with me about lyrics and stuff, and it's been completely wonderful.\"<ref>http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/all-that-remains-frontman-says-upcoming-album-is-far-and-away-better-than-a-war-you-cannot-win/</ref> A music video was made for 'This Probably Won't End Well'.\n\nThe album art for this album is based on an upwards view of the ceiling of the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] in Rome, Italy.\n\n==Musical style==\nPhil Labonte stated about the album: \"I think this record is far and away better than our [[A War You Cannot Win|last one]]. It's, in my opinion, far and away better than '[[Overcome (All That Remains album)|Overcome]]'.\" Personally, I think that we have a lot of songs on the new album that are better. He also stated: \"I think the record overall is probably leaning 'sing-y.' We've got 12 songs, and there's probably four or five songs that are beginning to end singing. There's some screaming worked into two or three.\"<ref>http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/all-that-remains-frontman-says-upcoming-album-is-far-and-away-better-than-a-war-you-cannot-win/</ref>\n\nDrummer Jason Costa stated about the album: \"It definitely still sounds like us. But the heavy stuff is heavier, and the faster stuff is faster. We all really challenged ourselves on this album. And the radio stuff is more\u2026 not more radio, but there's definitely more singing, there's more melody and stuff like that. But the songs are fast; we have a lot of fast burners on this album. And the double-bass stuff for the heavier songs is really challenging for me this time. The patterns are super-hard, some of them.\" <ref>http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/all-that-remains-drummer-is-absolutely-in-love-with-bands-just-completed-new-album/</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nUnlike the majority of the band's previous albums, ''The Order of Things'' received mixed to negative reviews from the critics.\n\n[[Ultimate-Guitar]] gave the album a score of 5.3/10, saying that \"the need to subdue the band's melodeath roots damages the full potential of the album, and the new raison d'\u00eatre to be 'catchy metal' has the band throwing their hat into a crowded and homogenized ring. Ultimately, this investment in a different sound doesn't pay off\".<ref>the need to subdue the band's melodeath roots damages the full potential of the album, and the new raison d'\u00eatre to be \"catchy metal\" has the band throwing their hat into a crowded and homogenized ring. Ultimately, this investment in a different sound doesn't pay off Retrieved 24 July 2015</ref>  Metalstorm.net gave the album a similar 5.6/10.  They lead their review with \"All That Remains moved so far away from the sound that originally made them famous, that I will be bound to use apologetic and vague phrases that both express my lack of love for what I am hearing and yet still admit that I understand how one could like it.\"<ref>http://www.metalstorm.net/pub/review.php?review_id=13215 Retrieved 24, July 2015</ref> [https://medium.com/@MusicRevRadar MusicReviewRadar] gave the record 2/5 stars stating that a tragic ballad sadly defined the main line of the entire record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medium.com/@MusicRevRadar/2015-under-the-radar-9e4644f5f04f|title=2015 Under The Radar|publisher=MusicReviewRadar|date=2016-04-13|accessdate=2016-04-20}}</ref>\nConversely Blabbermouth.net gave the album a positive 7.5/10, taking a more neutral standpoint on the controversial sound change.  \"Phil Labonte and his team are joyously doing whatever the hell they want, praise or scorn them all you like.\"<ref>[http://www.blabbermouth.net/cdreviews/the-order-of-things/ Phil Labonte and his team are joyously doing whatever the hell they want, praise or scorn them all you like.]  Retrieved 24 July 2014</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll lyrics written by Phil Labonte and all music by All That Remains.\n\n{{Track listing\n|title1 = [[This Probably Won't End Well]]\n|length1 = 3:48\n|title2 = [[No Knock]]\n|length2 = 2:48\n|title3 = Divide\n|length3 = 3:18\n|title4 = The Greatest Generation\n|length4 = 4:00\n|title5 = For You\n|length5 = 4:16\n|title6 = A Reason for Me to Fight\n|length6 = 3:42\n|title7 = Victory Lap\n|length7 = 3:54\n|title8 = Pernicious\n|length8 = 4:01\n|title9 = Bite My Tongue\n|length9 = 4:08\n|title10 = Fiat Empire\n|length10 = 4:04\n|title11 = [[Tru-Kvlt-Metal]]\n|length11 = 3:39\n|title12 = Criticism and Self-Realization<ref>https://www.amazon.com/The-Order-Things-That-Remains/dp/B00QXRNCTU</ref>\n|length12 = 7:03\n|total_length = 48:48\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline     = Japanese bonus track<ref>http://www.cdjapan.co.jp/product/QATE-10071</ref>\n| collapsed    = yes\n| title13      = We Are Only Human\n| length13     = 3:32\n| total_length = 52:20\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''All That Remains'''\n\n* [[Philip Labonte]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* Oli Herbert \u2013 lead guitar\n* Mike Martin \u2013 rhythm guitar\n* [[Jeanne Sagan]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Jason Costa]] \u2013 drums\n\n'''Additional'''\n\n* Josh Wilbur \u2013 production, mixing, mastering\n* Jim Fogarty \u2013 engineering\n* Justin Borucki \u2013 photography\n* Forefathers and Dan Bradley \u2013 design and layout\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2015)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australian Albums ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-albums-50-shades-of-grey-tops-chart-for-4th-week-20150307|title=ARIA Albums: 50 Shades Of Grey Tops Chart For 4th Week|publisher=Noise11|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|date=March 7, 2015|accessdate=March 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 72\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardCanada|17|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Oricon|150|M|artist=All That Remains|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/351104/products/1116502/1/|title=All That Remains - The Order of Things|publisher=oricn ME inc.}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|25|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardDigital|17|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardHardRock|3|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardIndependent|3|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRock|5|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardTastemaker|23|artist=All That Remains}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{All That Remains}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Order of Things}}\n[[Category:All That Remains (band) albums]]\n[[Category:2015 albums]]\n[[Category:Razor & Tie albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Order of Things\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]]\n| cover      = The Order of Things.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 24, 2015\n| recorded   = 2014\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]|[[hard rock]]|[[metalcore]]}}\n| length     = 48:48<br />52:20 (Japanese version)\n| label      = [[Razor & Tie]]\n| producer   = Josh Wilbur\n| prev_title = [[A War You Cannot Win]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[Madness (All That Remains album)|Madness]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Order of Things\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = No Knock\n | single1date = November 24, 2014\n | single2     = [[This Probably Won't End Well]]\n | single2date = January 13, 2015\n | single3     = [[Tru-Kvlt-Metal]]\n | single3date = February 10, 2015\n | single4     = For You\n | single4date = May 13, 2015\n | single5     = Victory Lap\n | single5date = December 8, 2015<ref>{{cite web|last1=Al-Sharif|first1=Rabab|title=All That Remains give fans a look at life on the road in video for new single \"Victory  Lap\"|url=http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/all_that_remains_premiere_video_for_new_single_victory_lap|publisher=Alternative Press|accessdate=January 22, 2016|date=December 8, 2015}}</ref>\n | single6     = Criticism and Self-Realization\n | single6date = May 4, 2016\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings \n| rev1 = [[About.com]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"About review\">{{cite web | url = http://heavymetal.about.com/od/allthatremains/fl/All-That-Remains-The-Order-Of-Things-Review.htm | title = All That Remains - The Order Of Things Review |publisher=[[MetalSucks]]|  first = Todd | last = Lyons | accessdate = February 21, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[Artistdirect]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Artistdirect review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/album-review-all-that-remains-the-order-of-things-5-out-of-5-stars/11314127 | title = Album Review: All That Remains \"The Order of Things\" \u2013 5 out of 5 stars |publisher=[[Artistdirect]]|  first = Rick | last = Florino| date = February 11, 2015 | accessdate = February 21, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-order-of-things-mw0002802858 | title = Album Review: All That Remains \"The Order of Things\" \u2013 2.5 out of 5 stars |publisher=[[AllMusic]] | first = Christopher | last = Monger}}</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Blabbermouth.net]]\n| rev4Score = 7.5/10<ref name=\"Blabbermouth review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/cdreviews/the-order-of-things/ | title = All That Remains - \"The Order of Things\" |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|  first = Ray | last = Van Horn, Jr.}}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[MetalSucks]]\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|1.5|5}}<ref name=\"MetalSucks review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.metalsucks.net/2015/02/17/remains-discuss-whiny-lead-singer-whose-controversies-far-outshadow-bands-bland-music/ | title = All That Remains To Discuss Is A Whiny Lead Singer Whose Controversies Far Outshadow His Band\u2019s Bland Music |publisher=[[MetalSucks]]| first = Kip | last = Wingerschmidt | date = February 17, 2015 | accessdate = February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev6 = [[Ultimate-guitar]]\n| rev6score = {{Rating|5.5|10|score=5.3 stars on a 10 point scale}}<ref name=Guitar>http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/reviews/compact_discs/all_that_remains/the_order_of_things/index.html</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Order of Things''''' is the seventh studio album by [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]]. It was released on February 24, 2015, on [[Razor & Tie]] Records. ''The Order of Things'' is the first studio album to be produced by Josh Wilbur. It is also the final album to feature bassist [[Jeanne Sagan]] due to her departure from the band in September 2015. The album debuted at number 25 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 19,150 copies in its first week only in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metalinsider.net/columns/metal-by-numbers/metal-by-numbers-34-the-kid-is-alright|title=Metal By Numbers 3/4: The Kid is alright|date=March 4, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe album was recorded and produced by Josh Wilbur.\n\nThe first song released from the album was \"No Knock\". The song was first posted by Labonte's pseudo-account called \"Harrison Ford\" with the video that was released on November 14, 2014 entitled \"You Found Me\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wxqQhxK35WY</ref>\nIt later on was posted by [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]] official [[YouTube]] Channel.\n\n[[Philip Labonte|Phil Labonte]] and producer Josh Wilbur wrote the lyrics for the album together, which is the first time in All That Remains catalogue. Phil Labonte stated about working with Josh: \"Honestly, the test for me is, like, when me and Josh [got] done, 'cause we wrote the melodies and the lyrics together; none of the vocals were done before I actually sat down with [[Josh wilbur|Josh]]. This is the first time that anyone has ever had any kind of input onto lyrics. But Josh is the only guy that's actually worked with me about lyrics and stuff, and it's been completely wonderful.\"<ref>http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/all-that-remains-frontman-says-upcoming-album-is-far-and-away-better-than-a-war-you-cannot-win/</ref> A music video was made for 'This Probably Won't End Well'.\n\nThe album art for this album is based on an upwards view of the ceiling of the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] in Rome, Italy.\n\n==Musical style==\nPhil Labonte stated about the album: \"I think this record is far and away better than our [[A War You Cannot Win|last one]]. It's, in my opinion, far and away better than '[[Overcome (All That Remains album)|Overcome]]'.\" Personally, I think that we have a lot of songs on the new album that are better. He also stated: \"I think the record overall is probably leaning 'sing-y.' We've got 12 songs, and there's probably four or five songs that are beginning to end singing. There's some screaming worked into two or three.\"<ref>http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/all-that-remains-frontman-says-upcoming-album-is-far-and-away-better-than-a-war-you-cannot-win/</ref>\n\nDrummer Jason Costa stated about the album: \"It definitely still sounds like us. But the heavy stuff is heavier, and the faster stuff is faster. We all really challenged ourselves on this album. And the radio stuff is more\u2026 not more radio, but there's definitely more singing, there's more melody and stuff like that. But the songs are fast; we have a lot of fast burners on this album. And the double-bass stuff for the heavier songs is really challenging for me this time. The patterns are super-hard, some of them.\" <ref>http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/all-that-remains-drummer-is-absolutely-in-love-with-bands-just-completed-new-album/</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nUnlike the majority of the band's previous albums, ''The Order of Things'' received mixed to negative reviews from the critics.\n\n[[Ultimate-Guitar]] gave the album a score of 5.3/10, saying that \"the need to subdue the band's melodeath roots damages the full potential of the album, and the new raison d'\u00eatre to be 'catchy metal' has the band throwing their hat into a crowded and homogenized ring. Ultimately, this investment in a different sound doesn't pay off\".<ref>the need to subdue the band's melodeath roots damages the full potential of the album, and the new raison d'\u00eatre to be \"catchy metal\" has the band throwing their hat into a crowded and homogenized ring. Ultimately, this investment in a different sound doesn't pay off Retrieved 24 July 2015</ref>  Metalstorm.net gave the album a similar 5.6/10.  They lead their review with \"All That Remains moved so far away from the sound that originally made them famous, that I will be bound to use apologetic and vague phrases that both express my lack of love for what I am hearing and yet still admit that I understand how one could like it.\"<ref>http://www.metalstorm.net/pub/review.php?review_id=13215 Retrieved 24, July 2015</ref> [https://medium.com/@MusicRevRadar MusicReviewRadar] gave the record 2/5 stars stating that a tragic ballad sadly defined the main line of the entire record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medium.com/@MusicRevRadar/2015-under-the-radar-9e4644f5f04f|title=2015 Under The Radar|publisher=MusicReviewRadar|date=2016-04-13|accessdate=2016-04-20}}</ref>\nConversely Blabbermouth.net gave the album a positive 7.5/10, taking a more neutral standpoint on the controversial sound change.  \"Phil Labonte and his team are joyously doing whatever the hell they want, praise or scorn them all you like.\"<ref>[http://www.blabbermouth.net/cdreviews/the-order-of-things/ Phil Labonte and his team are joyously doing whatever the hell they want, praise or scorn them all you like.]  Retrieved 24 July 2014</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll lyrics written by Phil Labonte and all music by All That Remains.\n\n{{Track listing\n|title1 = [[This Probably Won't End Well]]\n|length1 = 3:48\n|title2 = [[No Knock]]\n|length2 = 2:48\n|title3 = Divide\n|length3 = 3:18\n|title4 = The Greatest Generation\n|length4 = 4:00\n|title5 = For You\n|length5 = 4:16\n|title6 = A Reason for Me to Fight\n|length6 = 3:42\n|title7 = Victory Lap\n|length7 = 3:54\n|title8 = Pernicious\n|length8 = 4:01\n|title9 = Bite My Tongue\n|length9 = 4:08\n|title10 = Fiat Empire\n|length10 = 4:04\n|title11 = [[Tru-Kvlt-Metal]]\n|length11 = 3:39\n|title12 = Criticism and Self-Realization<ref>https://www.amazon.com/The-Order-Things-That-Remains/dp/B00QXRNCTU</ref>\n|length12 = 7:03\n|total_length = 48:48\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline     = Japanese bonus track<ref>http://www.cdjapan.co.jp/product/QATE-10071</ref>\n| collapsed    = yes\n| title13      = We Are Only Human\n| length13     = 3:32\n| total_length = 52:20\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''All That Remains'''\n\n* [[Philip Labonte]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* Oli Herbert \u2013 lead guitar\n* Mike Martin \u2013 rhythm guitar\n* [[Jeanne Sagan]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Jason Costa]] \u2013 drums\n\n'''Additional'''\n\n* Josh Wilbur \u2013 production, mixing, mastering\n* Jim Fogarty \u2013 engineering\n* Justin Borucki \u2013 photography\n* Forefathers and Dan Bradley \u2013 design and layout\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2015)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australian Albums ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-albums-50-shades-of-grey-tops-chart-for-4th-week-20150307|title=ARIA Albums: 50 Shades Of Grey Tops Chart For 4th Week|publisher=Noise11|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|date=March 7, 2015|accessdate=March 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 72\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardCanada|17|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Oricon|150|M|artist=All That Remains|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/351104/products/1116502/1/|title=All That Remains - The Order of Things|publisher=oricn ME inc.}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|25|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardDigital|17|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardHardRock|3|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardIndependent|3|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRock|5|artist=All That Remains}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardTastemaker|23|artist=All That Remains}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{All That Remains}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Order of Things}}\n[[Category:All That Remains (band) albums]]\n[[Category:2015 albums]]\n[[Category:Razor & Tie albums]]\n", "name_user": "191.125.163.122", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Order_of_Things_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Utah National Parks Council", "text_new": "{{Infobox WorldScouting\n|name=Utah National Parks Council\n|image=\n|type=council\n|owner=[[Boy Scouts of America]]\n|headquarters=[[Orem, Utah]]\n|location= \n|country=United States\n|coords=\n|f-date=\n|defunct=April 2020\n|founders=\n|founder=\n|members={{plainlist|\n*'''Youth:'''                 '''89,712'''\n<br>26,510  Cub Scouts\n<br>38,398  Boy/Varsity Scouts\n<br>14,286  Venturers  \n<br>10,518  Learning for Life\n(''includes Explorers'')             \n*'''Adults'''                  '''44,739'''\n*'''Units'''                      '''6,299'''\n*(Dec 31, 2014)\n}}\n|chiefscouttitle=President\n|chiefscout=Mike Neider\n|chiefscouttitle2=Council Commissioner\n|chiefscout2=Richard DuBois\n|chiefscouttitle3=Scout Executive\n|chiefscout3=David Pack\n|website={{URL|http://www.utahscouts.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Utah National Parks Council''' (UNPC) is a former local council of the [[Boy Scouts of America]] (BSA) that served youth in areas of [[Utah]] who live south of [[Salt Lake County, Utah]] and in some isolated areas of [[Lincoln County, Nevada|Nevada]] and [[Mohave County, Arizona|Arizona]]. It was headquartered in [[Orem, Utah]]. As of December 31, 2013, UNPC was the largest of {{Scoutstat BSA|councils}} local councils and is geographically within the [[Western Region (Boy Scouts of America)|Western Region]] of BSA.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last=Cathy|first=Allred|title=Scouting Activity Highest in Utah National Parks Council|url=http://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/article_c60bde92-9996-50de-b9b4-5de59e74ad19.html|accessdate=29 September 2011|newspaper=Daily Herald|date=28 February 2011}}</ref> In 2011, the UNPC was recognized by the [http://www.bestofstate.org/ Utah Best of State] Foundation as [http://www.bestofstate.org/winner2011_community.html Utah's Best Humanitarian Organization]. UNPC is a non-profit corporation governed by Scouting policies and a local community-based Executive Board.<ref>{{cite web|title=Executive Board Members and Assignments|url=http://www.utahscouts.org/openrosters/ViewOrgPageLink.asp?LinkKey=21740|work=UNPC Website|publisher=UNPC|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref> In April 2020, it combined with the former [[Great Salt Lake Council|Great Salt Lake]] and [[Trapper Trails Council|Trapper Trails]] councils to create the new [[Crossroads of the West Council]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/2020/03/10/boy-scout-councils-utah/|title=The LDS effect: Utah\u2019s Boy Scout councils will merge as their numbers slide|last=Stephenson|first=Kathy|newspaper=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|location=Salt Lake City|date=10 Mar 2020|accessdate=6 Apr 2020}}</ref> \n\n\n==Organization==\nUNPC is organized into 21 geographic areas known as Districts, each delivering Scouting programs to their local communities:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.utahscouts.org/OpenRosters/View_Homepage.aspx?orgkey=1197|title=Districts Boundary|website=www.utahscouts.org}}</ref>\nAlpine, Arapeen, Black Diamond, Bryce Canyon, Cathedral Gorge, Cedar Breaks, Great Basin, High Uintah, Hobble Creek, Iron Horse, Mount Nebo, Orem, Porter Rockwell, Provo Peak, San Juan, Snow Canyon, Tavaputs, Timpanogos, Wasatch and Zion District\n\n==Camps==\nUNPC operates eleven Scout camps and two high adventure bases throughout central and southern [[Utah]].<ref>{{cite web|title=UNPC Website|url=http://utahscouts.net/openrosters/view_homepage.asp?orgkey=290|work=Scout Camps|publisher=UNPC|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref> They include Maple Dell, Tifie, Blue Mountain, High Uintah, Scofield, Camp Eagle Mountain, and Thunder Ridge Scout Camps. Camp Jeremiah Johnson ([[Cub Scouting (Boy Scouts of America)|Cub Scout]] Day Camp) and Buck Hollow (Adventure Park for New [11 yr old] Scouts and Webelos [10 yr old] Wilderness Adventure) are camps dedicated to serving younger Scouts and Cubs. Entrada and Beaver High Adventure Bases serve primarily [[Varsity Scouting (Boy Scouts of America)|Varsity Scout]] teams and [[Venturing (Boy Scouts of America)|Venturing]] crews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maintour.com/utah/scout_camps.htm|title=Guide to Utah Scout Camps|work=MainTour|accessdate=November 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nUNPC also has Quail Creek Camp and Bacon Park Camp. These areas are used for unit and districts activities, family reunions, and council training courses.\n\nUNPC offers structured youth, adult Scouter, and family in-residence training courses at several of its Scout Camps.\n\n==== Wood Badge ====\n\nThe [[Wood Badge (Boy Scouts of America)|Wood Badge]] is the award given to those who complete the highest adult Scouter training course in Scouting. Courses are authorized by national BSA and are usually sponsored by a local council or region.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barnard|first=Mike|title=Wood Badge|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090802073002/http://www.woodbadge.org/21st.html |work=Wood Badge for the 21st Century|publisher=Mike Barnard|accessdate=2 October 2011}}</ref>\n  \n\"It is the mark of men who have demonstrated that they are men of character who are devoted to a cause: men who strive for perfection well knowing that even the best is not enough; men that hold the welfare of others above self; Scouters who live up to all that name implies.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The History of Wood Badge in the United States|year=1990|publisher=BSA|isbn=0-8395-4533-9|url=http://www.woodbadge.org/Ceremony/tinybeads.html}}</ref>\n\nUNPC offered 14 [[Wood Badge for the 21st Century]] courses in 2011 and trained 376 adult Scouters in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wood Badge Course Registration Listing|url=http://www.utahscouts.org/openrosters/ViewOrgPageLink.asp?LinkKey=21985&orgkey=2195|work=2011 Wood Badge Courses|publisher=UNPC|accessdate=2 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==== Timberline National Youth Leadership Training ====\nTimberline is what UNPC calls its [[National Youth Leadership Training]] courses. In 2010, UNPC trained 889 youth in this course over 12 summer weeks in 39 separate courses.<ref>{{cite web|title=Timberline Course Listing|url=http://www.utahscouts.org/openrosters/ViewOrgPageLink.asp?LinkKey=41584&orgkey=2195|work=Timberline|publisher=UNPC|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NYLT|url=http://www.scouting.org/scoutsource/BoyScouts/Resources/nylt.aspx|work=National Youth Leadership Training|publisher=BSA|accessdate=2 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Family camping ===\nUNPC used to offer an annual '''Family Camp''' program at Camp Maple Dell which allowed a whole family to participate in the fun activities associated with a Scout camp as a family and without an advancement focus.\n\nUNPC also offers a '''Family Odyssey''' program which is modeled after the [[Philmont Training Center]] experience at Tifie Scout Camp. This is a family program where a parent may attend Wood Badge, a Scout aged child may attend Timberline (NYLT), and the rest of the family may participate in age appropriate activities all at the same camp and all during the same week.<ref>{{cite web|title=Family Odyssey|url=http://www.utahscouts.org/openrosters/ViewOrgPageLink.asp?LinkKey=33117&orgkey=2195|work=Wood Badge with Family Odyssey|publisher=UNPC|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Eagles Nest==\nUNPC has a nationally sanctioned [[National Eagle Scout Association]] committee which recognizes new Eagle Scouts as well as notable Eagle Scouts from the council. \"Our council is the largest in the country, and we really have had the lead in Eagle Scout awards the last two years,\" said John Gaily, council program director. \"We are by far the most.\" In 2010, UNPC recognized 2,818 new Eagle Scouts.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nUNPC and [[National Eagle Scout Association|NESA]] recognize notable Eagle Scouts with either the [[List of Eagle Scouts (Boy Scouts of America)|Outstanding Eagle Scout Award]] or the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]]: Notable Eagle Scouts from UNPC include:<ref>{{cite web|title=Award Recipients|url=http://www.utahscouts.org/openrosters/ViewOrgPageLink.asp?LinkKey=41715&orgkey=2196|work=UNPC Website|publisher=UNPC|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Distinguished Eagle Scouts===\n<!-- only include those with Wikipedia articles -->\n*[[Christopherson Business Travel|Merrill D. Christopherson]], Entrepreneur, Awarded 1984\n*[[Dallin H. Oaks]], Administrator, Awarded 1984\n*[[Alan C. Ashton]], Entrepreneur/Corporate Officer, Awarded 1993\n*[[Jeffrey R. Holland]], Educator, Awarded 2000\n*[[Larry M. Gibson]], Entrepreneur/Corporate Officer, Awarded 2005\n*[[Wilson W. Sorensen]], Educator, Awarded 2007\n*[[Steven E. Snow]], Administrator, Awarded 2011\n\n==Tu-Cubin-Noonie Lodge==\nThe Tu-Cubin-Noonie Lodge of the [[Order of the Arrow]] was established in the UNPC on May 24, 1954.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tu-Cubin-Noonie Lodge History|url=http://utahscouts.net/openrosters/ViewOrgPageLink.asp?LinkKey=26638&orgkey=1203|work=UNPC Website|publisher=UNPC|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Scouting in Utah]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Utah National Parks Council}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://findingaid.lib.byu.edu/viewItem/MSS%205785  |title= Utah National Parks Council Records | work =  MSS 5785; 20th Century Western and Mormon Americana; L. Tom Perry Special Collections | publisher = Harold B. Lee Library, Brigham Young University}}\n\n\n{{Scoutorg BSA}}\n{{Scouting}}\n\n\n[[Category:Defunct local councils of the Boy Scouts of America]]\n[[Category:Western Region (Boy Scouts of America)]]\n[[Category:Youth organizations based in Utah]]\n[[Category:Orem, Utah]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox WorldScouting\n|name=Utah National Parks Council\n|image=\n|type=council\n|owner=[[Boy Scouts of America]]\n|headquarters=[[Orem, Utah]]\n|location= \n|country=United States\n|coords=\n|f-date=\n|defunct=April 2020\n|founders=\n|founder=\n|members={{plainlist|\n*'''Youth:'''                 '''89,712'''\n<br>26,51